                      <span>3</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-04-18</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>I worked for a high-tech company of around 300 people in 1996.  The president of the company purchased and loved "It's Not Luck" so much that he required all the people in the company to buy and read it.  At this time, his company was well-financed and very high-profile.
<br />
<br />The president implemented Goldratt's recommendations, and the company proceeded to spend the company's money on all the wrong projects.  He overfinanced his pet projects and pushed breadwinners out the door before they were ready to ship.  The company's products sold progressively more poorly, and the company finally declared bankruptcy and went out of business two years ago.
<br />
<br />If you're going to read a business book, you should read a business book written by a guy who knows how to do business.  Goldratt is a consultant who's out to sell books, not a guy who's actually done the things he proports to know how to do.  Check out www.goldratt.com if you think that's not true.
<br />
<br />Meanwhile, if you want to know how to run a company, go read "My Years with General Motors" by Alfred Sloan.  While Sloan's book also involves drawing bubble diagrams, it does not suggest that you can run a company by drawing pictures alone.</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">This one is good but The Goal is a lot better.</div>
